This article discusses an executive order issued by President Biden to reestablish the Federal Government as a leader in sustainability. The order sets forth various policies and goals aimed at addressing the climate crisis and achieving a carbon pollution-free electricity sector by 2035 and a net-zero emissions economy by 2050. The order includes targets for agencies to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, increase the use of carbon pollution-free electricity and zero-emission vehicles, achieve net-zero emissions buildings, and improve energy and water efficiency. It also emphasizes the importance of sustainable procurement and the engagement, education, and training of the federal workforce in sustainability and climate adaptation. The order establishes the Office of the Federal Chief Sustainability Officer and requires agencies to designate Agency Chief Sustainability Officers to lead implementation efforts. The order also emphasizes the incorporation of environmental justice considerations and collaboration with the public, private, and non-profit sectors.